#import "../../lib.typ": chapter

#chapter(13, "Walled garden of a world long past")[
  Mona's dad owned a computer, which Mona had barely touched.

  She was told stories about how they were crowned the greatest inventions of
  the 90s, and how it revolutionized how the world functioned as a whole, but
  she had only used it for her school assignments.

  It was natural for a girl who was born in the age of smartphones, which
  had quickly taken over the computing world from the hands of computers,
  to know nothing about the amazing tech.
  Despite its limitations in functionality compared to a fully-featured
  computer, mobile phones offered a much more polished and friendly user
  experience, which allowed it to take over all aspects of daily life.

  And now, Mona and her friends felt like their life would be nowhere-complete
  without their smartphones, while not knowing how a computer could exactly be
  useful for.

  Nevertheless, she felt intrigued about the world of computers. She had
  occasionally heard of IT specialists claiming that "mobile phones only had a
  fraction of the computing power that PCs have" and "if given a proper
  opportunity, computers could have outgrown smartphones by a wide margin".

  Hence, Mona walked in the IT clubroom, expecting to see a digital vintage
  world of some old technology, with a sprinkle of magic.

  What she saw definitely surprised her.

  _"Wires, wires everywhere!"_

  To accomodate the club's immense demand of electricity, power outlets and
  wires were placed everywhere throughout the clubroom. All the complex wiring
  were to power the computers, which there were about one or two dozens.
  Some members were sitting with their own computer, typing something to the
  machine with lightning speed.

  The male student standing in front of Mona introduced himself with an
  increasingly quieter tone. He was the club president, since he was in charge
  of maintenance for the club's infrastructure.

  Once the initial greeting was done, he invited the girls to get in to take a
  closer look. His swift navigation through the wiring reminded Mona of a ninja,
  which gave the three girls a general idea of what the IT club was supposed to
  be like.

  Mona tried to recall some of her knowledge from IT classes. Most of it was
  abstract jargon about information, data, and knowledge. Then, there were some
  assignments with some weird-looking computer programs.

  To use a computer was a wild ride, so buckle up. First, one had to use some
  educational program to get used to controlling the machine, via special
  devices known as the "mouse" and a "keyboard". The mouse was used to move a
  virtual pointer on the computer screen, and when the button on it was clicked,
  it acted somewhat like Mona tapped on a touchscreen device like her phone,
  with the only difference being the position of action was where the cursor
  pointed at. Honestly it was a pretty roundabout way to imitate a touchscreen,
  but some still claimed it was more "performant". Then, there was the keyboard,
  which was something alike the smartphone keyboard, but with more weirdly-named
  keys like _F6_ and _Pause_ other than the regular alphanumeric keys. As it was
  a purely physical device, it did not take up any screenspace at all, which
  Mona agreed would make it somewhat more convenient than the virtual keyboard
  of her smartphone.

  "Well... first, I guess... I will give a quick rundown of the club..."

  "Senpai, you got it!" Uta encouraged him in an encouraging tone.

  "Uhm... thanks." He continued, "Well, the club..., as you can see, was mainly
  about computers. Even though computers were just a small topic of the IT
  subject you learn at school, it is our main topic here."

  _"Right, since serious work can't be done with mobile phones, right?"_

  Computers were sophisticated devices which had more functionalities than
  smartphones, but it was exclusively used for work. If one wanted to browse
  social media, for example, you would have to download a smartphone emulator
  to run the social media app, which was about five to ten times slower than
  just running that app on a phone. And even though the social media company
  could just make a program that worked on desktop to browse that specific
  social media site, it was too much of a cost for a tiny user base.

  Recently, Mona also heard some short videos talking about the cost reason was
  just an excuse, and the real reason was to trap the app's user base in the
  walled garden ecosystem of mobile phones, which seemed to be something right
  from conspiracy theorists. Though, with how much anti-consumer practices had
  been popping up in popular apps, Mona began to wonder the integrity of such
  claims.

  Returning to the matter at hand, it seemed that Mona had dozed off from the
  conversation. Thanksfully, she could catch up by utilizing her extensive
  knowledge from 30-second fact videos to fill in the gaps.

  "So, there is this thing called competitive programming. You formed teams, and
  then try to solve a set of problems like any normal math or science test." The
  senpai talked in an intriguing tone, "But the answer is actually a program, so
  you gotta write code."

  "Programs? You mean the coding assignments in the final year of middle school?
  You can compete in writing that?" Mikoto replied with enthusiasm.

  "Right! And if you are good at this and got some awards, IT programs at some
  university would take you in instantly! A lot of graduates from the club got
  into their university without having to take any entrance exams because of it."

  Mona noticed that the president suddenly became able to converse much more
  freely than before. Maybe it was due to the topic was his forte now?

  "Really? Maybe I should take a try!"

  Illusioned with the idea of a free admission to college, Mikoto sat down at a
  computer box, experiencing first-hand the IT club experience. Meanwhile, Uta and
  Mona were both watching closely. Uta looked at the box with a doubtful gaze,
  skeptical of the "free admission ticket" the senpai just talked about.

  _"It has to be insanely hard, right?"_

  The president initially intended to hold Mikoto's hand to guide her mouse, but
  once he realized what he was intending to do, his cheek blushed before him
  giving up the idea entirely. Honestly, since it was Mikoto, she would not
  really care about it, but it seemed Uta and Mona had picked up on the signal.

  So, he instead pointed to a blue-ish icon on the top left, to which Mikoto
  moved her mouse cursor to before double-clicking on it.
  Then, a eye-piercingly blue interface popped up with all sort of weird and
  pixelated symbols. The president pressed some key combinations to get rid of
  everything on the interface, leaving just a couple of monospace text lines.

  "Wait, this isn't Kantan? What programming language is this?"

  "Kantan was mostly an educational language, so it's quite useless on tasks
  that are not drawing turtle graphics and writing to files. We are doing
  assembly programming, the REAL programming language by REAL programmers."

  "Assembly?" Mikoto's expression whitened, "It's the first time I had heard of
  it..."

  "Of course you norm-, won't know what Assembly is. It's not taught in schools."

  _"Was he really intended to say the word 'normies'..."_ Uta thought. _"Seems
    like our senpai here had some form of technological superiority complex...
    Well, at least he's not being rude in front of us, it's fine."_

  Despite Uta being a "normie", she surprisingly knew what "Assembly" was.

  "Hmm-, I remembered that name from some video I saw online." Uta cut into the
  conversation, "They said it's extremely difficult to program in, though."

  "Don't worry, it'll become much easier if you got the hang of it. See, this
  simple program only move 0 to the register `er1`, before returning control to
  the operating system."

  "Register? I don't think I'm following..." Mikoto smiled helplessly.

  "Oh, right, they did not introduce that in standard IT textbooks. Just think
  of it as a place data is placed, for now."

  "Uhm, I guess so... Like a file, perhaps?"

  "Let's see a more complex example!" The president, ignoring the misleading
  comparison his kouhai just made, put his hand on the keyboard and typed some
  code. When everything was done, he would then hit the `F6` button, which
  spawned a new console on the screen.

  "Tada, here is a program that prints 'Hello, World!'."

  However, the code of the program was now much more complicated, which left the
  three girls in pure disbelief.

  "You see, to print 'Hello, World!', you need to tell the operating system to
  do so, and that's via a _system call_ (syscall for short).
  On this specific machine, a
  syscall can be executed via setting `er1` to the syscall number, while other
  parameters are passed in `er2` to `er5`." The president continued, "Here, the
  syscall for printing is `0x621`, ah right, that's in hexadecimal, but that's
  unimportant, and it expects two parameters: the number of bytes printed and
  the pointer to the printed data, which I passed via `er2` and `er3`. Finally,
  to do the syscall, we use the `0x14` interrupt."

  _"System call? Hexadecimal? Pointers? What on earth is he talking about?"_

  The president became a talking textbook. And not an ordinary textbook, it was
  an advanced one for college undergraduates or something. The three girls
  could only digest about ten percent of the amount of technical jargon he just
  threw out.

  "I'm sorry, but I could only understand like a bit of that."

  "Oh, sorry! So here, you see, a system call is a message from your program to
  the operating system" He drawed a diagram on the board, "The operating system
  is the interface between your userspace program and the underlying hardware,
  like the screen for example."

  He ended up introducing even more technical terms than before. This was
  precisely the reason why Kantan was taught in compulsory education. The amount
  of Computer Science theory it required to write a proper Assembly program was
  about 30 percent of an average bachelor CS course. However, the explicit
  control of Assembly made programs written in it run much faster, which was
  crucial for programming contests, where the gap between an accepted solution
  and a time limit exceeded could be just a millisecond.

  After a while of explaining, finally the three girls could get the gist of
  things. They were still unclear whether the numbers "621" and "14" have to do
  with printing, but whatever.

  "So, if we change the data of the `.text` block and pass the new length in
  `er2`, it should print what we want to?"

  "You're right!"

  Mikoto made the modification, changing the generic 'Hello, World' to her
  name, before hitting the run button. Before that, she had changed the current
  language to Japanese, something she still rememberred vividly from her IT
  class with a word processor in middle school.

  She hit the F6 key, after mistakenly hitting F4 and F5, which fortunately did
  not cause anything to happen. The program ran for about one second, and
  the output was a English text: 'Program Termination', printed in crimson
  red. Regardless, it was not her name.

  "Heh? What did I do wrong?" Mikoto worriedly asked in shiver, "Did I break the
  machine or something..."

  She glanced at the computer box, trying to see smoke or any indication of
  things going wrong. The green LED light were still beeping in the same
  frequency as usual.

  "No, it's just a normal program error. Oh, the console can't handle Japanese
  words, I forgot to mention that it is English-only."

  Mikoto heaved a sight of relief. It would be a disaster if she had broken the
  machine and would have to compensate. If she recalled correctly, a PC box
  could cost up to one million yen, with the price of regular hardware ranging
  from one hundred to two hundred thousand yen.

  "So... Is there a way to fix this?" After composing herself, Mikoto asked.
  "Maybe somehow teach the machine some Japanese? I'm not sure..."

  "You can set the locale by the `0x1037` syscall, then enable experimental
  Unicode support via the `0xD600` syscall, and change the number of bytes to
  print to 8 because each Japanese characters is two-byte long..."

  After seeing the shocked expressions on the girls' face, the president finally
  paused.

  "Well... Maybe this is too advanced."

  "Erm-, no, it's okay, senpai! Thanks for your guidance..." Mikoto scratched
  her head, wryly smiling.

  While replying, the girl instinctively looked at the computer clock in the
  taskbar.

  "Ehhh! It's been fifteen minutes already!"

  The president's lengthy introduction to Assembly programming made the time
  went flying by like a jet coaster. The three girls hastily picked up their
  bags, saying their final greetings before heading out.

  While communicating absolutely nothing, in their minds, they were thinking the
  exact same thing.

  _"This place is too much for me!"_

  With no time for a break, they headed straight to the destination on their
  little club-visiting adventure.
]
